This ode was perhaps composed at the time of the Liberalia, like the third elegy of the fifth book of Ovid' s Tristia, but· m what year there are no means of detes-mining. Orelli says it appears to be copied from a Greek poem, because it approaches the ehu-mer of the dithyramb. Except' m the subject the resemblance does not strike me. If Horace had written on purpose to show the impossibility of reaching the force and beauty ,of the higher order of Greek lyrie poetry through the medium of his language, he could not have succeeded better, and the ἐνθουσιασμός, ‘ fumrss &c., which some commentators proiess to find in the ode, exist, I think, only in their own mistakeu conception of Horaoe’s mind and writings. They create the inspiration they expect to find. The subject is as likely to have been suggested by a Greek picture as a Greek poem, but neither hypothesis is necessary.
